						<div class="container">
							<h1 class="entry-title">A Yom Kippur love story: When Margot met Tamar</h1>

							<p id="entry-bg">
															<strong>Author:</strong> Danna Harman<br />
																					<strong>Source:</strong> <a href="http://www.haaretz.com/news/features/.premium-1.546426" target="blank">Ha'aretz</a><br />
																					<strong>Published:</strong> September 11, 2013														</p>

						</div>
						<div class="entry-content">
							<h6>For two women, a veteran Israeli and an American immigrant, a romance that began on the Day of Atonement led to a wedding</h6>
<p>Yom Kippur. It’s a day of atonement. A time of reflection. And probably one’s best opportunity to spend some quiet quality time with Hashem. And then there are those for whom it is also a romantic anniversary of sorts.</p>
<p>The two 30-year-olds look sheepish. “Well…” begins Tamar Madeson, glancing sideways. “The thing is…” says her wife Margot Stern, attempting to pick it up. The women look at each other. Tamar laughs. Margot blushes.</p>
<p>It started, as all new and hopeful things really should, right after Rosh Hashanah, four years ago.</p>
<p>Margot was not in a great place. She had just broken up with her girlfriend and moved out of the apartment they had shared for nearly two years. On a friend’s couch, she found herself skimming through her Facebook inbox and noticed a week-old message she had never opened. The headline was “Hey Schmoopie.”</p>
<p>“Hey Schmoopie?” Margot repeats slowly, looking at Tamar with a raised eyebrow. “I had no idea who was writing to me.”</p>
<p>“You know, like in Seinfeld,” replies Tamar, a Jerusalemite, brightly explaining U.S. pop culture to her South Florida-born and -bred partner.</p>
<p>The message was friendly, kind and easygoing — like Tamar herself. Something like “Hi! Hope life is good. Please send your girlfriend big hugs and take care and Shana Tova.”</p>
<p>When Margot failed to respond, says Tamar, it was no big deal. “I was, like, ‘Oh well,’” she says.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.haaretz.com/news/features/.premium-1.546426" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','http://www.haaretz.com']);" target="_blank">Read the full story on Ha&#8217;aretz</a> (some browsers require logging in)</p>
<p><a href="http://awiderbridge.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/1933871354.jpg" ><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-14751" alt="1933871354" src="http://awiderbridge.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/1933871354.jpg" width="100%" /></a></p>
						</div>
